erver injects those."},"792":{"id":"/integrations/web-ui-54","page_id":"/integrations/web-ui","type":"text","url":"/integrations/web-ui#post-apirun","content":"Success response (200):"},"793":{"id":"/integrations/web-ui-55","page_id":"/integrations/web-ui","type":"text","url":"/integrations/web-ui#post-apirun","content":"json is the parsed stdout when it is valid JSON, otherwise null."},"794":{"id":"/integrations/web-ui-56","page_id":"/integrations/web-ui","type":"text","url":"/integrations/web-ui#post-apirun","content":"curl example (with optional bearer token):"},"795":{"id":"/integrations/web-ui-57","page_id":"/integrations/web-ui","type":"text","url":"/integrations/web-ui#publishing-maintainers","content":"Publish hyper-pm first, then hyper-pm-web, using pnpm publish from each app so workspace: ranges rewrite correctly. Details in apps/hyper-pm-web/README.md."},"796":{"id":"/integrations/web-ui-58","page_id":"/integrations/web-ui","type":"text","url":"/integrations/web-ui#publishing-maintainers","content":"type: info"},"797":{"id":"/integrations/web-ui-59","page_id":"/integrations/web-ui","type":"text","url":"/integrations/web-ui#publishing-maintainers","content":"For terminal-first workflows and every CLI flag in one place, see Examples and the CLI reference."},"798":{"id":"/intro/architecture","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"page","content":"Architecture","url":"/intro/architecture"},"799":{"id":"/intro/architecture-0","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"text","url":"/intro/architecture","content":"How the data branch, JSONL log, worktrees, and projections fit together."},"800":{"id":"/intro/architecture-1","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"heading","url":"/intro/architecture#high-level-flow","content":"High-level flow"},"801":{"id":"/intro/architecture-2","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"heading","url":"/intro/architecture#repository-layout-conceptual","content":"Repository layout (conceptual)"},"802":{"id":"/intro/architecture-3","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"heading","url":"/intro/architecture#event-sourcing-mindset","content":"Event sourcing mindset"},"803":{"id":"/intro/architecture-4","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"heading","url":"/intro/architecture#sync-as-a-side-channel","content":"Sync as a side channel"},"804":{"id":"/intro/architecture-5","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"heading","url":"/intro/architecture#wrappers-share-one-binary","content":"Wrappers share one binary"},"805":{"id":"/intro/architecture-6","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"text","url":"/intro/architecture#high-level-flow","content":"init creates or adopts an orphan branch (no parent commit) that holds hyper-pm data, and writes .hyper-pm/config.json in your working tree."},"806":{"id":"/intro/architecture-7","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"text","url":"/intro/architecture#high-level-flow","content":"Most mutating commands run against a temporary Git worktree checked out at the data branch, append one or more lines to the event log, commit, and optionally push — your primary branch is untouched."},"807":{"id":"/intro/architecture-8","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"text","url":"/intro/architecture#high-level-flow","content":"Reads replay the log (with schema versioning) into an in-memory projection of epics, stories, tickets, and sync cursors."},"808":{"id":"/intro/architecture-9","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"text","url":"/intro/architecture#repository-layout-conceptual","content":"Exact filenames on the data branch are owned by the CLI implementation; treat them as opaque except through supported commands."},"809":{"id":"/intro/architecture-10","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"text","url":"/intro/architecture#event-sourcing-mindset","content":"Think of the JSONL file as an append-only journal:"},"810":{"id":"/intro/architecture-11","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"text","url":"/intro/architecture#event-sourcing-mindset","content":"Each line is a typed event (for example TicketCreated, GithubInboundUpdate)."},"811":{"id":"/intro/architecture-12","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"text","url":"/intro/architecture#event-sourcing-mindset","content":"Deleting entities is modeled as soft deletes via events, not rm on rows."},"812":{"id":"/intro/architecture-13","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"text","url":"/intro/architecture#event-sourcing-mindset","content":"doctor validates that the log can be read and replayed; use it in CI or before releases if you rely on automation."},"813":{"id":"/intro/architecture-14","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"text","url":"/intro/architecture#sync-as-a-side-channel","content":"GitHub is a projection target, not the source of truth for hyper-pm’s core model. Outbound sync updates issues; inbound sync (full mode) translates issue changes back into events when they differ from what hyper-pm last wrote."},"814":{"id":"/intro/architecture-15","page_id":"/intro/architecture","type":"text","url":"/intro/architecture#wrappers-share-one-binary","content":"hyper-pm-web and hyper-pm-mcp spawn the same bundled CLI (dist/main.cjs) that you would run in a shell. That keeps UI, agents, and scripts aligned — there is no second implementation of business rules in the web layer."},"815":{"id":"/intro/overview","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"page","content":"Overview","url":"/intro/overview"},"816":{"id":"/intro/overview-0","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview","content":"What hyper-pm is for, how it stores data in Git, and when to use GitHub sync."},"817":{"id":"/intro/overview-1","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"heading","url":"/intro/overview#what-hyper-pm-is","content":"What hyper-pm is"},"818":{"id":"/intro/overview-2","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"heading","url":"/intro/overview#what-it-is-not","content":"What it is not"},"819":{"id":"/intro/overview-3","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"heading","url":"/intro/overview#interfaces","content":"Interfaces"},"820":{"id":"/intro/overview-4","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"heading","url":"/intro/overview#optional-github-issues-sync","content":"Optional GitHub Issues sync"},"821":{"id":"/intro/overview-5","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"heading","url":"/intro/overview#ai-assisted-fields","content":"AI-assisted fields"},"822":{"id":"/intro/overview-6","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#what-hyper-pm-is","content":"hyper-pm is a Git-native project manager: epics, stories, tickets, comments, and sync metadata live in your repository on a dedicated data branch, not only in a SaaS database. The CLI (and anything that wraps it) mutates state by appending typed events to a JSONL log and replaying them to build the current projection."},"823":{"id":"/intro/overview-7","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#what-hyper-pm-is","content":"That design gives you:"},"824":{"id":"/intro/overview-8","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#what-hyper-pm-is","content":"Offline-first workflows after clone and fetch — no hosted PM required for local reads and writes."},"825":{"id":"/intro/overview-9","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#what-hyper-pm-is","content":"Reviewable history of who changed what, suitable for compliance-minded teams."},"826":{"id":"/intro/overview-10","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#what-hyper-pm-is","content":"Disposable worktrees for mutations so your main checkout stays clean while the tool edits the data branch."},"827":{"id":"/intro/overview-11","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#what-it-is-not","content":"A full replacement for GitHub Projects, Jira workflows, or cross-repo portfolio views out of the box."},"828":{"id":"/intro/overview-12","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#what-it-is-not","content":"A multi-tenant hosted service: security and backups are your Git hosting and practices."},"829":{"id":"/intro/overview-13","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#interfaces","content":"Surface"},"830":{"id":"/intro/overview-14","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#interfaces","content":"Role"},"831":{"id":"/intro/overview-15","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#interfaces","content":"hyper-pm CLI"},"832":{"id":"/intro/overview-16","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#interfaces","content":"Canonical API: init, CRUD on epics/stories/tickets, work, comment, sync, audit, doctor, repo helpers."},"833":{"id":"/intro/overview-17","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#interfaces","content":"hyper-pm-web"},"834":{"id":"/intro/overview-18","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#interfaces","content":"Local browser UI that shells the same CLI bundle; good for browsing and editing without memorizing flags."},"835":{"id":"/intro/overview-19","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#interfaces","content":"hyper-pm-mcp"},"836":{"id":"/intro/overview-20","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#interfaces","content":"stdio MCP server exposing hyper_pm_run so agents can invoke the CLI with structured JSON."},"837":{"id":"/intro/overview-21","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#interfaces","content":"type: warn"},"838":{"id":"/intro/overview-22","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#interfaces","content":"Treat MCP and the web API as powerful local automation: only enable them in environments you trust, and prefer binding the web server to loopback unless you have auth and TLS in front."},"839":{"id":"/intro/overview-23","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#optional-github-issues-sync","content":"With sync --with-github (and credentials), hyper-pm pushes ticket changes to GitHub Issues, pulls inbound edits, and can attach PR timeline signals for eligible tickets with linked PR references (not done / cancelled). Opening a PR can record GithubPrActivity and move the ticket to in_progress. Plain sync is git-only. See GitHub sync for details."},"840":{"id":"/intro/overview-24","page_id":"/intro/overview","type":"text","url":"/intro/overview#ai-assisted-fields","content":"Some ticket commands support --ai-draft and --ai-improve when HYPER_PM_AI_API_KEY is set. These call out to your configured AI provider from the CLI environment — review outputs before committing them to shared tickets."}},"count":840},"sorting":{"language":"english","sortableProperties":["content","page_id","type","keywords","tag","url"],"sortablePropertiesWithTypes":{"content":"string","page_id":"string","type":"string","keywords":"string","tag":"string","url":"string"},"sorts":{"content":{"docs":{"1":805,"2":311,"3":810,"4":814,"5":622,"6":342,"7":122,"8":766,"9":725,"10":541,"11":663,"12":163,"13":396,"14":638,"15":571,"16":399,"17":331,"18":305,"19":395,"20":169,"21":200,"22":158,"23":161,"24":397,"25":323,"26":480,"27":97,"28":160,"29":109,"30":759,"31":249,"32":675,"33":740,"34":607,"35":333,"36":262,"37":330,"38":159,"39":572,"40":226,"41":378,"42":187,"43":380,"44":231,"45":795,"46":381,"47":245,"48":256,"49":252,"50":672,"51":671,"52":253,"53":727,"54":748,"55":746,"56":603,"57":584,"58":609,"59":688,"60":314,"61":610,"62":126,"63":578,"64":611,"65":179,"66":180,"67":678,"68":685,"69":176,"70":450,"71":580,"72":499,"73":783,"74":535,"75":823,"76":188,"77":162,"78":110,"79":211,"80":649,"81":371,"82":369,"83":302,"84":679,"85":686,"86":166,"87":133,"88":684,"89":332,"90":254,"91":186,"92":666,"93":246,"94":673,"95":286,"96":135,"97":257,"98":767,"99":339,"100":680,"101":573,"102":483,"103":177,"104":182,"105":82,"106":581,"107":495,"108":44,"109":784,"110":534,"111":38,"112":212,"113":650,"114":37,"115":681,"116":574